# Change Git Remote URL to a Local Repository

You can update your Git remote URL to point to a **local repository path** instead of an online URL.

---

## âœ… Step 1 â€” Check Current Remote URL

```bash
git remote -v
```

Example output:

```
origin  https://example.com/repo.git (fetch)
origin  https://example.com/repo.git (push)
```

---

## âœ… Step 2 â€” Set Remote URL to Local Path

Use `git remote set-url` and provide the local repository path.

### Linux / macOS

```bash
git remote set-url origin /home/user/projects/my-local-repo.git
```

### Windows

```bash
git remote set-url origin C:\Users\user\projects\my-local-repo.git
```

---

## âœ… Step 3 â€” Verify the Change

```bash
git remote -v
```

Now the remote should display your local path.

---

## ðŸ“Œ Alternative Using File Protocol

```bash
git remote set-url origin file:///home/user/projects/my-local-repo.git
```

---

## ðŸ”„ Alternative Method (Remove and Add Remote)

```bash
git remote remove origin
git remote add origin /path/to/local/repo.git
```

---

## ðŸ§  Summary

Changing the remote URL to a local path allows Git to:

* Push to a local repository
* Pull from a local repository
* Work without a remote server

